@{ui}@{i}> > Ok, now you're forcing me to respond.  Who's to say that the ring around
@{ui}@{i}> > that particular planet isn't composed of metal, reflective particles?  If
@{ui}@{i}> > were, I see no reason why you wouldn't see a reflection of the ship passing
@{ui}@{i}> > by.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> If I were to hazard a guess (I've only seen the rotten show twice) I would
@{ui}@{i}> say its mostly a matter of scale.  In order to see the reflection at that
@{ui}@{i}> size, the ship would have to be several thousand miles long.  The ship is
@{ui}@{i}> large in comparasion to the rings because it is closer to the camera than
@{ui}@{i}> the planet, and consequently, not a few feet above them as the reflection
@{ui}@{i}> would have you believe.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}
Ok, that's a good answer.  I hadn't thought of that.  Hope I don't get
flamed too hard over it.

Jim Shinosky


