@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Wed, 31 Jan 1996 23:19:00 -0500 " link day.31 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Curtis Carlson " link from 0514} @{i}<Curtcee@AOL.COM> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Global Brush Problem" link subj 0770}
---
In response to my problem about a global brush map leaving a seam across a
reflective table top on 1/30 Bill Boyce wrote:

@{i}>Try 'rolling' your brushmap in an image processor like ADPro (don't know
@{ui}what the PC >has) so the join is in the middle of the image. This may shift
the edges enough to be >away from the table top. Or apply the brush to the
table as a reflection (?) map, rather >than in Globals, so you can rotate
it's axis until the seam is invisible.

Well, I don't have ADPro but I do have Picture Man for Windows and Fauve
Matisse and I have no idea what "rolling" the image is in either of those
programs. I did try the reflection map idea and it does work to eliminate the
seam from the table top but it would also eliminate the reflection of the
clouds in another object that flies through the scene. The reflection map
once applied to an object is static. It is locked to the object. So for an
object that is supposed to be flying through the scene it won't work. For the
table that remains still, yes; for the objects that move, no. My original
intention was to use the ground with the cloud texture over the scene and all
reflective objects would reflect these clouds. In trying to do that I
discovered the bug that in trace mode the horizon set in the globals box
moves in alignment with the camera (an earlier post of mine) so I rendered
the ground/cloud texture alone and used it as a background still and as a
brushmap in the globals box to work around that problem. And it worked great
up until the seam showed up.

On 1/31 Martin Caspersson wrote in response to the same problem:

@{i}>The solution is not to use a ground plane but a normal plane scaled just
@{ui}enough to
@{i}>fill the picture.
@{ui}
Tried it. Didn't work. Same effect. Same seam. At first I thought it would
work, then I realized that the brush is really the same either way, a 640x480
picture that has to be wrapped. I'm about to give up and just leave it the
way it is.

Curtis Carlson
Curtcee@aol.com


