@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Thu, 1 Feb 1996 20:24:13 +0000 " link day.01 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Phil Stopford " link from 1116} @{i}<pstopfor@JESUS.OX.AC.UK> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: New Show" link subj 1039}
---
On Thu, 1 Feb 1996, Andrew Herbert wrote:

@{i}> >> be new over there.  While it has it's strong points, the story line is
@{ui}@{i}> >> not as well developed nor the graphics as good as Babylon 5.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> >I've read that Babylon 5's story line was writen for 5 television seasons
@{ui}@{i}> >before it first showed on TV.  And the story is very well planed out.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> I remember someone someone saying this to me before, although with the main
@{ui}@{i}> star (Micheal O'Hare) quitting after the first series you have to ask how
@{ui}@{i}> planned the next four series are.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> I don't like Bab5 that much for reasons I won't go into (just in case I
@{ui}@{i}> start a war here) but the graphics in are very good, I especially like the
@{ui}@{i}> planet sequences and (of course) the battle scenes.  I like the stuff that
@{ui}@{i}> give impressions of forces, for example how the ships react to the thrusters
@{ui}@{i}> give a very nice effect of force and mass along with the way the guns recoil
@{ui}@{i}> when they fire.  The only thing I dislike about it is the way they use the
@{ui}@{i}> same panels textures again and again, we don't see much real life damage on
@{ui}@{i}> the station or ships much such as battle scars or burns but the models look
@{ui}@{i}> very good and although some of the scenes are very well animated.  I think
@{ui}@{i}> doing what I do as a hobby often forces me into watching rendered stuff on
@{ui}@{i}> tv and I find myself often wincing when I see a raytrace which looks like
@{ui}@{i}> it's been done on videscape.  I remember watching a trailer for Unexplained
@{ui}@{i}> Mysteries and seeing a flying saucer taking off which was basically
@{ui}@{i}> comprised of loads of lightwave lensflares.  And someone payed real money
@{ui}@{i}> for that.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> Anyway, to the main subject of Imagine if you want to create a Lightwave
@{ui}@{i}> lesflare then just get someone to render one for you on a black background
@{ui}@{i}> then use this as a colour map and also use the negative image as a filter
@{ui}@{i}> map... hey presto, a lightwave lensflare in imagine (make sure you align it
@{ui}@{i}> to the camera).
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> I wonder if impulse could come up with a lightwave-alike lensflare for
@{ui}@{i}> imagine although  the current lensflare effect can be tweaked to give great
@{ui}@{i}> results.  I liked lightwave lenflares when I first saw them they've been
@{ui}@{i}> used so often on tv you soon get sick of the sight of them.  Whilst we're
@{ui}@{i}> still on this sci-fi thread does anyone know what happened to Amblin's plans
@{ui}@{i}> to ressurect DrWho?  My nomination for the new DrWho would probrably be
@{ui}@{i}> Julian Clary.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}I got a pretty good imitation - well it suffices anyway. Make a default
disk and apply the twinkle texture to it, locking it to the default state
in the box provided. Remember to rotate it so the z axis sticks out of
the disk and alter the settings until you're happy with it (in version
4.0 you can look in the little preview box). Exit all the requesters by
clicking OK and then pick the disk and create a state called default with
shape enabled.
Open a new project and load in the disk under action editor. Delete the
exisitng alignment bar and make the disk track to the camera. Now in the
stage editor scale it until it's oval and save changes. Now if you render
it and the settings are right you shoudl get a reasonable imitation and
since twinkle affects the filter, it is also transparent.
I don't know what you professional types will think of it, but it's the
best I've been able to come up with anyway - any improvement suggestions
are welcome.
As are any plasma bolts and shield flare effects (not using Essence textures)

Phil.


