@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Fri, 2 Feb 1996 07:54:19 +0100 " link day.02 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Martin Caspersson " link from 0939} @{i}<SA9418@IDA.UTB.HB.SE> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Global Brush Problem" link subj 0770}
---
@{i}> 2) Even if he'd applied the brush onto a huge plane, Imagine wouldn't
@{ui}@{i}> have shown the gigantic pixels as a seam, since Imagine anti-aliases all
@{ui}@{i}> brushmaps. If the two pixels each took up half the screen, for example,
@{ui}@{i}> you wouldn't see a sudden change where one gigantic pixel ends and the
@{ui}@{i}> other begins, but rather a smoooooth color gradation.
@{ui}
What happens is that there are a dark and a light half of the ground
with a color graduated seam in between. You can see that they
actually are two big pixels by zooming out from the plane. The image
on the ground will become less and less pixellated as you do.



