---
Charles wrote:

@{i}>One question: what size was the wall's axis before you stretched it? If
@{ui}@{i}>you created a wide, thin wall (say, XYZ = 300 by 5 by 30) without
@{ui}@{i}>changing the default size, that wall's axis was 32,32,32 units in
@{ui}@{i}>length. This axis size has no relationship to the object's actual
@{ui}@{i}>dimensions unless you specifically change the _axis only_ to reflect the
@{ui}@{i}>object, or if your object is a simple primitive.
@{ui}
Actually I imported a cube. Missing primitive cubes in Imagine, I have them
stashed on file in different resolutions (4by4by4, 12by12by12 points etc.)
So, if I understand you then, I should change the axis to be the same size as
the object ? I should also make the wall the size I want it, and then relate
the brick size in the texture to the wall size, not vice versa 'cause the
bricks will scale with it, right?

Come to think of it, the "size" in the trans. requestor did say 32by32by32,
and 32 was one of the brick's dimensions, so maybe I had like one large brick
covering the whole wall, and that's why it didn't show up ? Then when I
resized the wall, the bricks resized with it?

@{i}>> Do the size numbers in the texture requester have
@{ui}@{i}>> anything to do with the Imagine size units used on objects ?
@{ui}
@{i}>Yes, they're the same. If you use the Checks texture and specify a check
@{ui}@{i}>size of 32, the black & white squares will be the exact same size as if
@{ui}@{i}>you'd modelled a plane 32 x 32 units.
@{ui}
So tell me, does the texture sizing relate to the AXIS size, or the OBJECT
size ?

@{i}>I would also avoid objects that are thousands of units in size, because
@{ui}@{i}>of Imagine's 32K (64K?) unit limit on the little world you place
@{ui}@{i}>objects, lights, and camera into. Often, you need to place the camera of
@{ui}@{i}>some lights fairly far away from objects, and if a large object occupies
@{ui}@{i}>2/3 of your virtual soundstage, that doesn't leave much room to back up.
@{ui}
In your experience, what is a good size range to use for, say, a human
environment replication. You know, walls, buildings, etc. where you want the
camera view and lighting to represent an average height human ? Would it be
perhaps 10 Imagine units to 1 foot, or 100 to 1 or more like 1 to1 ?

Thanks for your reply, Charles. You're always a life-saver.
Nancy
NancyJcbs@aol.com


