@{ui}@{i}> >
@{ui}@{i}> >Did you use the neat little formula?    :)
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> Which formula was that?  I just conformed the text I made in the spline
@{ui}@{i}> editor around a cylinder with various values until I got the right spacing.
@{ui}
Conny posted a handy-dandy formula on the list a coupla weeks ago
pertaining to conformations. I didn't memorize it, but I have it on file
if you need it.

@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> Another problem I have is setting the axix exactly in the middle of the text
@{ui}@{i}> ring so it will rotate properly.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}
This is probably why you're getting a wobble. Try this: after you've done
your conform to sphere operation, select the object and slice it. Just by
itself. This will automagically center your axis and size it to the
proportions of your object. Pretty handy. =)

@{i}> >
@{ui}@{i}> >>      then positioned the axis to the center of the ring of text. I intend
@{ui}@{i}> >>to simply rotate this string of text around a sphere (logo).
@{ui}@{i}> >
@{ui}@{i}> >>I gave this ring of text a 10 degree x-rotation to slant down, exposing more
@{ui}@{i}> >>of the logo, and giving it the old "Universal Pictures" effect.
@{ui}@{i}> >
@{ui}@{i}> >>Problem is, when it rotates, it wobbles.  I tried rotating the x axis back
@{ui}@{i}> >>to normal, but it still wobbles.
@{ui}@{i}> >
@{ui}@{i}> >How are you rotating it in your scene? By the "rotate" effect or using
@{ui} states?
@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> I'm using the cycle editor.  Does states do this better?
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}
Yeech. Pardon me if I'm wrong, but weren't States created to replace the
cycle editor? I think you'll find a much easier method with the Rotate
stage FX.

@{i}> >
@{ui}@{i}> >How did you cant the text-ring? You didn't realign the axis to the world's
@{ui}@{i}> >coordinates afterwards, did you? (I hope not, because you shouldn't.)
@{ui}@{i}> >If you rotate that thing around it's local z-axis it ought to work.
@{ui}@{i}> >
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> I just rotated the ring 10 degrees along the x-axis (local).  I expected the
@{ui}@{i}> whole thing to rotate steadily along the new axis, like a space station, but
@{ui}@{i}> it wobbles instead.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> >Can you use the "rotate" effect using local coordinates?
@{ui}@{i}> >
@{ui}
Yes, you can. In fact, you CAN'T use it with world coordinates!

