@node 0192 "Message number 0192"

@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Mon, 5 Feb 1996 11:29:52 -0500 " link day.05 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Tom Ross " link from 1282} @{i}<rosst@UNVAX.UNION.EDU> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Space-Time and Beyond" link subj 1300}
---
I'm watching this discussion enjoyably, but at an uninformed distance. To
y'all physics types:

Didn't some astromers just discover stars with planet complexes? Does
this weigh mightily? and

What about quantum physics and quantum logic? Is this demonstrable in the
ordinary meat&potatoes, knives'n'forks physical world, so that I can
point to something on the kitchen table and say, 'See, by observing this
object I'm subtly changing it!'? I know of this only from a couple of
pop-science books, Space-Time and Beyond and The Dancing Wu Li Masters. and

How, if at all, would this exotic info affect Imagine users' depictions
of space-time?

On Sun, 4 Feb 1996, Jim Belcher wrote:

@{i}> >>If an explosion still occures the debris will spread spherically and
@{ui} continue
@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> >>outward for as long as there is nothing to stop it. On ground the debris
@{ui} will
@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> >
@{ui}@{i}> >aha, but what about gravitational pulls of planets, stars, or even blackhole
@{ui}@{i}> >stars (assuming these actually exist).  At the end of the day it's up to
@{ui}@{i}> >your own imagination to come up with something that looks good, not
@{ui}@{i}> >necessarly realistic (although realism is a good place to start).
@{ui}@{i}> >
@{ui}@{i}> >
@{ui}@{i}> You pull the chain of an aging physicist.  Depending on your perspective,
@{ui}@{i}> I believe you are both correct. The gravitational pull of other planets,
@{ui}@{i}> etc. will affect the trajectory of the debris, but only very slightly. If
@{ui}@{i}> observed at the moment of the explosion, parts would appear to go out in
@{ui}@{i}> all directions in straight lines.  However, if sufficient time were allowed
@{ui}@{i}> to pass, the debris would be seen to have deviated from a simple, straight
@{ui}@{i}> line path, by the influence of gravity from planets, etc.  But we're talking
@{ui}@{i}> about significant amounts of time here, and I think the question is probably
@{ui}@{i}> how things appear visually immediately after the explosion.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> I'd argue that it's possible to have an explosion
@{ui}@{i}> (instant release of energy) without oxygen (example: an atomic bomb). I'd
@{ui}@{i}> agree that the explosion is limited to the material in whatever happens to
@{ui}@{i}> on the object exploding. Space is just that: space. It does make sense that,
@{ui}@{i}> without additional sources of energy present, the explosion is going to be
@{ui}@{i}> over rather quickly.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> At the moment of the explosion, it should appear to be roughy sperical in
@{ui}@{i}> shape.  With only weak outside forces present, the force of the explosion
@{ui}@{i}> should be almost equally distributed in all directions.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> A personal favorite: the rocketship scene from "When Worlds Collide". Flames
@{ui}@{i}> from the spaceship rocket burn upward while in space.  Good movie; bad
@{ui}@{i}> physics.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}

			@{"   Return  to  Main    " link main}
			@{"Return to Natural Index" link natural}
@endnode
@node 0193 "Message number 0193"

@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Mon, 5 Feb 1996 23:02:27 1100 " link day.05 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Darryl Lewis " link from 0532} @{i}<Darryl_Lewis@COMLINK.MPX.COM.AU> @{ui}
