@node 0257 "Message number 0257"

@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Wed, 7 Feb 1996 07:30:36 -0800 " link day.07 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Marc Reinig " link from 0894} @{i}<moose@ICO.COM> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: more bad bricks(texture scaling)" link subj 1492}
---
Charles,

@{i}>Theoretically, you should get a wall that's 5 times as large, but with
@{ui}@{i}>the same pattern of bricks: 2 layers of about 3 bricks each. That's
@{ui}@{i}>because __when you edit an object's axis, textures and brushes are
@{ui}@{i}>affected in the same manner__. This is logical: if you spend 2 hours
@{ui}@{i}>getting the textures on a goose just right, you should be allowed to
@{ui}@{i}>scale it down to make goslings, without having to readjust the textures
@{ui}@{i}>for the smaller object. So, when you scale, move, or rotate the axis of
@{ui}@{i}>an object, all the textures/brushmaps applied to that object scale, move,
@{ui}@{i}>or rotate right along with it. (Whether you're also scaling the points,
@{ui}@{i}>or just the axis, is irrelevant to textures/brushes.)
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>However, in this case, IT DOESN'T WORK. Why?
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}
Well, one way to divide textures into groups is by whether scaling the
object should scale the texture itself. In your gosling example it makes
great sense not to scale the gosling textures (Essence? <G>).

However, with the bricks, if I build a wall and I want to make it a larger
or smaller wall, I just want the wall to get larger, not the bricks. So, at
least, in that sense, for bricks texture, there is some logic for not
scaling the texture with the object. I don't know if that's what they had in
mind but ...

As they say, "Who knows the mind of God." or in this case, Imagine.

-Marco


			@{"   Return  to  Main    " link main}
			@{"Return to Natural Index" link natural}
@endnode
@node 0258 "Message number 0258"

@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Thu, 8 Feb 1996 03:35:18 +1100 " link day.08 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Jodi Nelson " link from 0795} @{i}<jodi@C031.FOCALTECH.COM.AU> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Rolling Text" link subj 1230}
---
At 06:10 PM 2/6/96 -1000, you wrote:
@{i}>I'm stuck here. Trying to get a line of text (just two words)
@{ui}@{i}>to run at an angle in an animation, but make it look like it
@{ui}@{i}>hits a roller coaster type of path.  I've created the path in
@{ui}@{i}>the detail editor, and tried to align it in stage editor, but
@{ui}@{i}>that doesn't work.  Do I have to use states for something like
@{ui}@{i}>this?
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>Yes, I do have a manual, by the way :-)  I just choose to read
@{ui}@{i}>it after nothing else works.  I find out interesting things
@{ui}@{i}>along the way ;]
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>Damon
@{ui}
I have done this before. All you have to do is delete the position and
alignment bars for the text object (in the action editor). Add them again
selecting follow path for the position bar and align to path then conform
group to path for the alignment bar. The text should then folow the path
while conforming to it's shape.
Last time I used this effect I tracked the camera to the text object then
made it follow a larger version of the same path. The result was a writhing
string of text which stayed in the centre of the screen.

Oh by the way, you may have to rotate the axis for the text object in the
detail editor to make sure it it facing the right way when it is aligned to
the path.
Sorry for my vague instructions. I hope you can make sense of them.

Jodi


