@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Fri, 9 Feb 1996 08:19:13 -0800 " link day.09 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Chuck Needham " link from 0445} @{i}<twobit@globaldialog.com> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Imagine reviews" link subj 0321}
---
I just recieved my March Digital Video Mag. It has a comparison of 4 Mac
and 10 PC 3D-rendering packages. Although I was glad to see Imagine
(version 4.0) among the list, I was rather dismayed by the terse review
and low rating. Now matter how glowing a review may be the negatives are
what stick in peoples minds, and in this case, because of the absence of
informative descriptions of the "strong points" and features "at which
Imagine excels.", the negative connotations are overwelming to the
cassual reader and "Imagine unaware".; like: "from the 'old school' of
3D", "so you spend time", and "a program technical people would love...
Power users will love it".

IMHO the reviewer (who has been around the block a few times) assumed the
general readership were somewhat familiar with Imagine already and didn't
give them enough information even to be curious about the capability of
the software. Certainly not as much as other of the packages reviewed.
The only real clue as to the strengths of Imagine were in the single
comparison chart, tallying more "dots" than any other program listed. But
who would see that, after reading the text review.

Maybe the "least said the least damaging" to a program that didn't look
and feel like his "obvious" favorites.

Irritated.

I also checked the DV website for the additional charts covering modeling
and rendering elements for the reviewed programs as directed by the
article...not there yet. I think these charts should have been part of
the printed magazine (another diservice to the readership.)

--
Chuck Needham
2Bit Graphics
e-mail: twobit@globaldialog.com
http://www.globaldialog.com/~twobit/


			@{"   Return  to  Main    " link main}
			@{"Return to Natural Index" link natural}
@endnode
@node 0333 "Message number 0333"

@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Fri, 9 Feb 1996 10:57:34 -0500 " link day.09 }
