@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Fri, 9 Feb 1996 13:57:27 GMT0BST " link day.09 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"129275 J PADFIELD " link from 0146} @{i}<CS9H4PJQ@SWANSEA.AC.UK> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: BrushWrapping" link subj 0583}
---
@{i}> My problem is one concerning brushwrapping. Here's what I wanted to do:
@{ui}@{i}> I'm trying to create a city. By night.. Something like new york... That's
@{ui}@{i}> really cool yeah, I know. However, when I create a skyscraper by night I
@{ui}@{i}> figure all I have to do is create a beam and apply a 'light' brush to it...
@{ui}@{i}> For the front of the skyscraper that would be fine. 100's of lights cover
@{ui}@{i}> the front. The side however contains only stripes. If I use any
@{ui}@{i}> combination of BrushWrapping (Z- or X-Axes wrapping) I don't get any
@{ui}@{i}> lights at all!! How do I get this rite without applying 4 brushes to the
@{ui}@{i}> beam?
@{ui}
Further to earlier answers, you could try using a procedural texture
rather than a brush-map. I created a skyscraper by creating 2 large
towers. One was black, and the other yellow with the BRIGHT attribute
turned on. The yellow one was scaled down very slightly and placed
inside the black one. Then I applied the RectWin texture to the black
block, and the yellow block kind of shows through the "holes" that
RectWind cuts in the outermost block, giving the impression of
windows with lights on inside. Play with the size and settings of the
texture until you get something you like.

Hope this makes some sense to you. By the way, this was not an
original idea. I saw it a long time ago, probably on this list.
Thanks to whoever came up with it originally.

Cheers, Jimmy.


			@{"   Return  to  Main    " link main}
			@{"Return to Natural Index" link natural}
@endnode
