@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Fri, 9 Feb 1996 23:34:44 +0100 " link day.09 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Conny Joensson " link from 0485} @{i}<cjo@KIRUNA.SE> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: BrushWrapping" link subj 0583}
---
@{i}>However, when I create a skyscraper by night I
@{ui}@{i}>figure all I have to do is create a beam and apply a 'light' brush to it...
@{ui}@{i}>For the front of the skyscraper that would be fine. 100's of lights cover
@{ui}@{i}>the front. The side however contains only stripes. If I use any
@{ui}@{i}>combination of BrushWrapping (Z- or X-Axes wrapping) I don't get any
@{ui}@{i}>lights at all!! How do I get this rite without applying 4 brushes to the
@{ui}@{i}>beam?
@{ui}
Rick B's trick with rotating the brush 45 degrees around Z ought to work.
But there is actually a texture that makes windows, "rectwind".

Create a tall box.
Make it yellowish and bright.
Copy and paste it.
Scale the copy a bit larger than the original.
Make it black and not bright.
Apply "rectwind" (you'll have to figure out the setting yourself though).
When rendered you should get some sort of skyscraper with a pattern og lit
windows (the yellowish box showing through the windows generated by the
texture).

