@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Fri, 9 Feb 1996 19:12:57 -0800 " link day.09 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"John Prusinski " link from 0806} @{i}<jprusins@CYBERGRAFIX.COM> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Imagine reviews" link subj 0918}
---
@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>I disagree, Impulse has done quite a bit promoting Imagine.  Over the last
@{ui}@{i}>several years I have seen quite a few ads in DV., CGW, and AVvideo, selling
@{ui}@{i}>Imagine and other impulse products.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}
Unfortunately, most of these ads were apparently written by (and possibly
designed by) someone with the same professional skills as the person who
wrote the 3.0 docs: bad grammar, misspellings, and poor, cluttered page
layout won't impress anyone looking for a new piece of 3D software.

@{i}>
@{ui}The only reason
@{i}>that LW gets the kind of press it does is because NewTEK's toaster, and
@{ui}@{i}>shows like B5 and Seaquest.
@{ui}
Actually, B5 and SeaQuest were (surprisingly enough) NOT created as
promotional vehicles for NewTek products.  The creators of those shows chose
LW because it's economical, efficient, and capable of stunning results.  A
certain company in Minnesota might learn a lesson from this about the value
of making your software easy to learn and use.  They spend a lot of time
talking about how they keep their sofware cheap for its power by adding
features instead of spending time and money on interface and
documentation.... when Imagine costs as much (or more) than the competition,
this excuse won't hold water anymore!

Just my NSHO... :^)

John.


