@{i}>>I just started using Real 3D, but before I purchased, I looked closely
@{ui}@{i}>>at other products including Lightwave and 3D Studio. In my opinion
@{ui}@{i}>>Imagine is getting left in the dust.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>Real 3D has only recently started advertising their product in CGW and other
@{ui}@{i}>mags.  Real 3D has a much smaller user base than Imagine.  Real 3D also has
@{ui}@{i}>a reputation of being a very difficult interface to master and that has
@{ui}@{i}>turned off a lot of people.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}
Real 3D has been advertising for quite awhile. Not as long as Impulse, but
at least since the PC version has been available.

(another snip)

@{i}>Imagine has as many features or more than 3DS or Lightwave.  The only reason
@{ui}@{i}>that LW gets the kind of press it does is because NewTEK's toaster, and
@{ui}@{i}>shows like B5 and Seaquest.  As far as 3DS, the modeler sucks, the interface
@{ui}@{i}>is difficult to use ,too many nested menus, no metaballs, no algorithmic
@{ui}@{i}>textures.  How can you say it's better?  The only reason it has more
@{ui}@{i}>popularity is because it has been around for 5 years on the PC, and a lot of
@{ui}@{i}>gaming companies bought into it when there was nothing else available.  Sure
@{ui}@{i}>it has a lot of plugins but most of the great plugins are features built
@{ui}@{i}>into imagine.  Most of 3DS's plugins cost more than Imagine.    The
@{ui}@{i}>rendering quality is nowhere near as good as Imagine unless you are
@{ui}@{i}>comparing scanline.  The only thing that makes it a good choice for gaming
@{ui}@{i}>companies is the fact that it has network rendering support, better scanline
@{ui}@{i}>features and plugin availability.  It's main advantage is that it has been
@{ui}@{i}>out longer and there is no amount of advertising that any company can do to
@{ui}@{i}>lessen that advantage.   Fact is Autodesk has a great advantage by having
@{ui}@{i}>cornered the maket early enough to get the high-end developers to support
@{ui}@{i}>it.
@{ui}
Well, 3DS does have some more advantages: proper, excellent documentation
and a supportive company. The manuals for 3DS are among the best I've ever
seen (and I've written some manuals), with a great set of tutorials. You
will know how to use the program after you work through the tutorial book.
And, I doubt anyone would ever be called a "sh*thead" if they called
Autodesk technical support, as has happened during calls to Impulse. And
while it's only IMHO, I think 3DS has an easier to use interface than
Imagine. But program interfaces are something that can be argued over
endlessly without solution.

(yet another snip)

@{i}>
