@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Mon, 12 Feb 1996 12:10:05 EST " link day.12 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Robin Luiten " link from 1183} @{i}<luiten@TRANTOR.NMSD.OZ.AU> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: aspect and res.." link subj 1452}
---
@{i}> In a message of 10 Feb 96 Granberg Tom wrote to me:
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>  Hi Tom
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>  GT> What is the correct resolution & aspect ratio for: pc-lores when doing
@{ui}@{i}>  GT> a FLC
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> You can calculate it your self!.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> An aspect ratio is the relationship between the width of an item to its
@{ui}@{i}> height, expressed in this form:
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>    width : height
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> For example, a 1:1 aspect ratio means that the item is as wide as it is
@{ui}@{i}> high. Aspect ratios are described by saying their width value to their
@{ui}@{i}> height value. Taking the previous example, you would say that it has a
@{ui}@{i}> one-to-one aspect ratio!.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> Image aspect refers to the aspect ratio of the image itself. A 640x400
@{ui}@{i}> image has an image ratio of 640 : 400, or more simply, 8 : 5.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> Hope that cleared things!. :)
@{ui}
Nope! Sorry but I think you have forgotten one thing.

You forgot to account for the fact that the 640x400 display is actually
being displayed on a monitor that is wider than it is high. Basically
the width to height ration of monitors is  1.33 to 1. [Yes there are
monitors out there with different aspects but they are no common]

Therefore talking your example of 640x400 you get your relative width
to height ration of 8 : 5. Talking into account the 1.33 to 1 ratio
of the monitor you get  8/1.33 to 5 / 1.  There fore you get an aspect
ration of: 6 to 5 or near enough  [in fractional form its 1.20 to 1 ]

NOTE: PC displays of 320x240, 640x480 and 1024x768 are "square" or
      1 to 1 aspect ratios.

Hope that helps.

Robin Luiten


