@node 0533 "Message number 0533"

@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Wed, 14 Feb 1996 07:41:50 -0800 " link day.14 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Marc Reinig " link from 0894} @{i}<moose@ICO.COM> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Lights and Shadows" link subj 0984}
---
@{i}>light source (L1) positioned at its centre.
@{ui}@{i}>Also placed in the scene is another light source (L2) of the the right
@{ui}@{i}>side of the camera, this light was placed in the stage editor.
@{ui}@{i}>refer to ascii diagram below.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>                             o
@{ui}@{i}>                          o     o
@{ui}@{i}>                        o    L1   o
@{ui}@{i}>                       o           o
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>                                             L2
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>                             \/
@{ui}@{i}>                           camera
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>L1 and L2 are both lights of diminishing intesity with the same intesity
@{ui}@{i}>values, L2 is the only shadow casting light source.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>Initially I ray-traced the scene only using the Light L1, I then added
@{ui}@{i}>L2 but when the ray trace was complete the shadows from L2 had darkened
@{ui}@{i}>the surfaces that had previously been fully illuminated by L1.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>What is going on, if L2 was of greater intensity than L1 you should be able
@{ui}@{i}>to see shadows, but the shadows cast by L2 should not darken areas
@{ui}@{i}>that are illuminated by L1.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}
No, you will see shadows regardless of the relative intensity of L1 and L2.

The depth of the shadow depends on the relative intensity of L1 and L2 and
their distances to the objects in question.

The unshadowed area that are lit are lit L1+L2.

The shadowed areas are lit by only L1.

Thus you would expect to see a shadow on the surface where one part is
unshadowed and is receiving L1+L2 and the adjacent part is shadowed and
receiving only L1.

-Marco


			@{"   Return  to  Main    " link main}
			@{"Return to Natural Index" link natural}
@endnode
@node 0534 "Message number 0534"

@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Wed, 14 Feb 1996 11:06:03 -0500 " link day.14 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Ben Alkov " link from 0236} @{i}<balkov@VNET.NET> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Iml direction; newbie questions" link subj 0934}
---
Thanks very much for your reasoned and reasonable reply. I'm glad you took
the time to understand my concerns and respond to them, instead of
responding to my tone (bad day).

I appreciate the helpful suggestions, however, a note and a discovery are
in order.

the note: himem.sys is a memory manager/provider. Imagine *does* need a
memory manager

@{i}>>Now to prove the helpfulness of my nature - Imagine has its own memory
@{ui}@{i}>>management, so don't try using anything else.
@{ui}@{i}>>Boot from DOS.
@{ui}@{i}>>This is all you need in your config.sys file:
@{ui}@{i}>>DOS=HIGH,UMB
@{ui}@{i}>>Device=F:\WINDOWS\Himem.Sys
@{ui}
The discovery: I finally tried booting w/ a *really* minimal config (a la
the above) under dos 6.2 (NOT 7.0!) WITHOUT (this is the important part, I
think) STACKER.

No stacker=Imagine runs like a dream w/ plenty of free ram.
Stacker=Imagine flakes


