---
Mikael Johannsen wrote:
@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> Hi
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> I saw the NBC news last night. They showed a real life laser powerfull
@{ui}@{i}> enough to destroy missiles and half the price of a Patriot missile. Guess
@{ui}@{i}> now we have a realistic model to design our own realistic laser weapons.
@{ui}
        Well, REAL lasers are rather boring as weapons...  We are
so used to seeing a laser as a VISIBLE beam of light, yet real
lasers don't look like a glowing tube.  Instead, they are invisible
unless something gets in their way.  So, if you SEE  a laser beam
you are really seeing the laser reflected off the dust and dirt in
the air.  The more dust/dirt/etc in the air the more of the beam
you would see.  I didn't see the laser on NBC, but we have a laser here
at Penn State the the meteo dept uses durring the summer and on a cloudy
night or when there is a lot of dust in the air, you can see the beam go
off into space.  It's kinda neat, but not really as impressive as the
"fake" lasers we see in movies.

        Basically, if it looks good then does it HAVE to be realistic?

Chris.


--
