@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Sat, 17 Feb 1996 18:38:12 -0600 " link day.17 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{" Stephen G.  " link from 0062} @{i}<sgiff@AIRMAIL.NET> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Imagine on an SGI!!!!!" link subj 0901}
---
At 10:04 PM 2/17/96 +0000, you wrote:
@{i}>On Sat, 17 Feb 1996, Marc Reinig wrote:
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>> > Imagine, which won't run under Windows 95, is now running
@{ui}@{i}>> > happily on an SGI.
@{ui}@{i}>>
@{ui}@{i}>> I was under the impression that several people had Imagine running on a
@{ui}@{i}>> Win95 machine. I don't think it runs on in a DOS box and you can't multitask
@{ui}@{i}>> (wait for Imagine for Windows) but it does run.
@{ui}@{i}>Yep imagine does run under win 95, but only if you press F8 on startup
@{ui}@{i}>and select "dos prompt only".
@{ui}
Well if you press F8 and then Dos prompt only, then that is all you have a
dos prompt and that is not running under Windows 95.  That is running under
DOS 7.0.  Imagine will not run under any version of Windows, OS2, NT or any
thing that uses DPMI memory management period!   Unless you use the Pharlap
hack.  Booting to a dos session or running from Dos with Win 95 on your hard
drive does not equal running under Windows anything.  Sorry, there has been
some confused posts about this and I felt the need to vent.

s.g.
@{i}>
