@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Ted Stethem " link from 1264} @{i}<tstethem@LINKNET.KITSAP.LIB.WA.US> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Howdy" link subj 0845}
---
On Mon, 12 Feb 1996, Jean Wong wrote:

@{i}> <edit>
@{ui}@{i}> I am also a Truespace 2 user, and I've been trying to bring in some complex
@{ui}@{i}> (>10,000 vertices) DXF objects from TS2 into Imagine. They seem to transfer
@{ui}@{i}> okay, except that some of the faces (~5%) seem to be "flipped," that is, when
@{ui} I
@{i}> quickrender, they become black holes. Then I have to go in and point edit each
@{ui}@{i}> face/vertex to get them to render properly. Any of you have that kind of
@{ui}@{i}> problem?
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> problem.  Any suggestions?
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}  The normal on these polygons are flipped so you are seeing the back
side of the polygon (which appears as a hole). I don't know the exact reason
why but many convertors do this when converting to Imagine TDDD (or maybe
more correctly, Imagine does this to imported objects). Imagine doesn't
care about the direction of normals, when the object is made within
Imagine. You might try some object convertor that will flip the polygons
so all the normals are facing out.


