@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Sun, 18 Feb 1996 10:48:31 PST " link day.18 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Andrew Nunn " link from 0205} @{i}<apn_iml@MOBY.DEMON.CO.UK> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Animation" link subj 0519}
---
@{i}>        Another GREAT pd utility (for compiling your frames into anims) is
@{ui}@{i}>BuildAnim.  Supports all the faster anim formats, like anim7 and anim7l.
@{ui}@{i}>Makes for remarkable playback speeds, even on my humble 25mhz A3000.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>It is NOT a 24bit anim builder, but, with Rend24 (also PD) running in the
@{ui}@{i}>background, I convert my incoming 24bit frames to, in my case, DCTV
@{ui}@{i}>frames, which BuildAnim then handles nicely.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>Of course, for the Amiga, it's hard to beat ViewTek, for an all round
@{ui}@{i}>great anim/pic viewer.  Also PD.
@{ui}
I've recently started using a small utility I found on an Aminet CDRom.
It's called Easy_Mpeg. Its an Arexx script which has a little GUI front
end. It sits there in the background (like Rend24) and compiles them
to an MPEG file. I then copy the animation over to the PC for viewing. In
the absence of an ADPro Mpeg saver, it's the next best thing.

I'm doing things this way because I read some time ago that the mpeg
compiling programs on the PC don't like Imagines' output files. Somebody
suggested Abobe Premiere, but when I tried the demo version, it just kept
crashing (GPFing). Needless to say I didn't spend GBP350 buying the full
version as a result.

Andrew Nunn
