@node 0701 "Message number 0701"

@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Mon, 19 Feb 1996 15:10:41 +0000 " link day.19 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Jeremy Peter Hopkin " link from 0766} @{i}<jph@CS.NOTT.AC.UK> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Memory" link subj 0989}
---
@{i}> I am working in 40 meg of ram and the scene I am doing now drops out
@{ui}@{i}> aspects of the last object placed in it in scanline but will complete the
@{ui}@{i}> image in raytrace.  It appears I am on the line, but I'm wondering which
@{ui}@{i}> efforts might maximize my efficiency and allow me to add a bit more.
@{ui}
Don't worry you can raytrace a seen as complex as you like, as long as, you
can load it. The reason why scanline drops polygons, is it has a maximum,
number of polygons, in a scanline(horizontal pixel line).

However, trace calculates for each individual pixel, thus does not suffer
from memory constrants in the same way.

eg I have scanlined a scene(v.complex), and lost about 10 objects and some
of the others only had half their polygons. I traced it, the rendering time
went from hours to days, and everything was, there, inc. softshadows(40+lights)

                Jeremy


