@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Mon, 19 Feb 1996 15:28:22 -0500 " link day.19 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Prophet " link from 1135} @{i}<jbk4@PSU.EDU> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Some Info" link subj 1276}
---
@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>Here are a few things you can do:
@{ui}@{i}>        1. Lower RSDP to 3. This controls the number of multiple reflections, a
@{ui}@{i}>nd
@{ui}@{i}>transparent layers you can see through.
@{ui}@{i}>        2. Lower AARC to 4 or 9, the default of 128 is WAY too high. This
@{ui}@{i}>controls the level of oversampling on the new AA (which you turn on by changing
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>the OLDA to False).
@{ui}@{i}>        3. EDLE is the last parameter to consider. This controls how similar in
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>color pixels have to be in order for them to be antialiased. Larger values mean
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>only pixels that are significantly different in color will be antialiased. If
@{ui}
@{i}>you're just doing tests or very high res images you may want to raise this valu
@{ui}@{i}>e
@{ui}@{i}>up to, say, 75 to speed things up. When you want a more polished look for final
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>renderings lower this to 3 - 10 (but expect a slow-down), to antialias almost
@{ui}
@{i}>all pixels, even if they are very close in color. Never use a value of 0.  Some
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>people also like to render at higher resolutions with poor AA, and then simply
@{ui}
@{i}>scale them down to the size they need. This is another form of resampling that
@{ui}
@{i}>you may like.
@{ui}@{i}>        4. Do not cram alot of polygons into a very small area. Imagine will
@{ui}@{i}>render faster if polygons are distributed among more Octrees (read: objects are
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>larger).
@{ui}@{i}>        5. Use shadows, reflections, filtering, and refraction judiciously.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>If I think of anything else I'll let you know. Maybe others can put in their 2
@{ui}
If you are using an A2000 or A500, you can slightly better your time by
 displaying
a lores, 2colour screen.  This cuts down on the DMA usage required by Imagine's
HiRes screen.

You can also opt to use brushmaps instead of procedural textures.  With Forge,
you can design repeatable brushmaps from Essence Textures.  This isn't always
appropriate but do it when you can.  Using maps will require more memory though
so there is a trade-off.

Be careful with your use of transparencies.  I recently did a project that
required hundreds of bushes lining a desert road.  I couldn't have enough
decent looking bushes by creating detailed polygon objects because it required
too much memory.  I opted to apply transparency maps to 4 point planes.  This
gave me the look I needed but the rendertime went thru the roof.

Jaeson K.
