@node 0737 "Message number 0737"

@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Mon, 19 Feb 1996 23:46:54 -0800 " link day.19 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Ted Stethem " link from 1264} @{i}<tstethem@LINKNET.KITSAP.LIB.WA.US> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: OctVolume ???" link subj 1111}
---
  You will probably get a hundred answers to this question with some more
technical than others. Basically, there is a limit to the size of the
Imagine "universe". You can't have a scene in the stage editor that
extends beyond a radius of about 16,000 Imagine units, if I remember
correctly. That include lights, the camera and any objects. One way to
remedy this is to select everything in the Stage Editor and scale it down
until the boundaries of your scene do not extend past the limit.  The
other thing is set the size bar value in the Action Editor for Globals to
0 and let Imagine determine the world size. If you want to experiment,
you can enter your own values once you become familiar with this and
possibly optimize the render performance. The only caveat with the
scaling method is that Imagine render times increase significantly if
your world size becomes too small. Steve Worley explains it much better
in his book, "Understanding Imagine 2.0", still a very valuable source of
information for Imagine, even in its 4th incarnation.

