@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Tue, 20 Feb 1996 12:55:47 +0000 " link day.20 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Jeremy Peter Hopkin " link from 0766} @{i}<jph@CS.NOTT.AC.UK> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Memory" link subj 0989}
@{i}              <960219213225_327083941@emout10.mail.aol.com>
@{ui}---
@{i}>>Don't worry you can raytrace a seen as complex as you like, as long as, you
@{ui}@{i}>>can load it. The reason why scanline drops polygons, is it has a maximum,
@{ui}@{i}>>number of polygons, in a scanline(horizontal pixel line).
@{ui}
@{i}>That's interesting, and something I did not know.  It seems I remember having
@{ui}@{i}>objects drop out in trace before on me though.  At least in earlier versions.
@{ui}@{i}> I only use scanline to check images and animate with.  All my still scenes
@{ui}@{i}>are always traced.  Could anyone else confirm that trace will not drop out an
@{ui}@{i}>object as long as the scene will load?
@{ui}
Actually, I'm quite sure, it works everytime, do seem to remember having
objects drop out, but the threshold (if ther is one) is a mite larger than
scanline.

But I can tell you why trace goes faster when you scale things up and why if
objects go outside of the ground size(on quickdraw ground), they dissappear.

Imagine uses and octtree to raytrace. This is a way of splitting up a scene
to reduce the intersection calculations.

If you set "gridsize" in stage editor to 1024, then this will outline the
object boundry _inside_ of which objects will get traced. The octree, is a
method of splitting the area up into sections of eight(I believe..), on all
three axis and then specifing whether, and ojects exist in each section. If
objects do exist in a section, then, it further subdivides etc. until either
there is only one object in each section or the maximun depth is reached.

@{i}>From this, when it raytraces, it calculates the section of the octree the
@{ui}ray is in(ray comes from camera), and does its intersection calcuations, with
_only_ and _all_of_ the things in that section.

Thus if scene is big and fills the entire section (I'm not sure whether the
camera must be in the section) and objects are spread out then the octree will
split them up nicely. However, if you objects are small and very cramped
together then the octtree will reach maximum depth before its started splitting
the scene up much, thus each ray that passes into that octtree subdivision
(almost all if it fills the camera view) will do and intersection calculation
with _every_item_in_the_scene!!!!!

                ok

                        Jeremy


			@{"   Return  to  Main    " link main}
			@{"Return to Natural Index" link natural}
@endnode
@node 0749 "Message number 0749"

