@node 0783 "Message number 0783"

@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Wed, 21 Feb 1996 00:42:14 +0100 " link day.21 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Per Sverre Wold-Hansen " link from 1075} @{i}<woldh@MOTHER.NORCONNECT.NO> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Digital film resolution (Was: Some Info)" link subj 0140}
---
@{i}>I've seen the mention of 300Mb frames before. What they mean, I suspect, is
@{ui}@{i}>that the data to create each frame is up to 300Mb. A film res frame would be
@{ui}@{i}>no more
@{ui}@{i}>10 to 15 megs for the completed image, uncompressed.
@{ui}
@{i}>Bill Boyce * Animation * 3D,2D even 1D (a line in your choice of colour)
@{ui}
Balancing halfway off IML topics:

To my knowledge f.ex. the Quantel Domino film image processing
system operates at a maximum they term 4K. (Film digitized
frame-by-frame, digitally processed, transferred back to film.)

The Domino has been extensively used on lots of present motion
picture releases. I saw it demonstrated at SIGGRAPH '95 where
they showed removal of wires in FX-shots where trucks are
turned over during explosions, etc.

The 4K refers to horizontal pixel resolution, ie. 4000 pixels.

At a 4:3 aspect ratio this would mean 12,000K pixels at 24bit depth:

       = 36MB pr frame
       ===============

(Just HAVE to mention: Domino plays back 24 fr/sec in full
resolution, real time!)

     ** Per Sverre **
    Fredrikstad Norway
     woldh@sirius.no


			@{"   Return  to  Main    " link main}
			@{"Return to Natural Index" link natural}
@endnode
@node 0784 "Message number 0784"

@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Wed, 21 Feb 1996 00:42:17 +0100 " link day.21 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Per Sverre Wold-Hansen " link from 1075} @{i}<woldh@MOTHER.NORCONNECT.NO> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Edge Line Prob" link subj 0652}
---
@{i}>I've been trying to use the "Set Edge Line," and "Fill to Edge Line" to
@{ui}@{i}>seal up some sliced objects. But every time I get a "Bad Edge List -
@{ui}@{i}>Ignored" and it's no go.
@{ui}
Since I encountered problems myself in the beginning when trying
out this feature, here is a small cookbook:

1. Select the individual edges in sequence along one of the edges
   where you want your seam. My experience is that You'll have to
   do this MANUALLY one by one. Multipick with lasso etc. won't work.

2. Choose "Set Edge Line"

3. Deselect the edges by clicking somewhere outside the object.

4. Then repeat the process for the edges on other side of the seam.

5. Now choose menu: "Fill to Edge Line".


     ** Per Sverre **
    Fredrikstad Norway
     woldh@sirius.no


