At 02:16 PM 21/2/96 -0500, you wrote:
@{i}>John Prusinski wrote:
@{ui}@{i}>> Sorry, I can't resist jumping in on this anymore... What planet does
@{ui}@{i}>> one have to come from to consider a 5-year old 4-or-8-bit paint
@{ui}@{i}>> program preferable to a high-resolution 32-bit natural media program
@{ui}@{i}>> (Fractal Painter)?  I admit that the animation tools in Painter are
@{ui}@{i}>> fairly slow
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>The kind of planet where you spend 90% of your time in DOS, programming,
@{ui}@{i}>occational game playing, and running Imagine.  The kind of planet where
@{ui}@{i}>you want to quickly pop into your painting program to adjust a universal
@{ui}@{i}>palette or adjust a pixel or two.
@{ui}
Amen. DPaint is great for quick-and-dirty, and indispensable for animation.
Also, DPaint is not "a 5-year old 4-or-8-bit paint program". It's still
current - recently got V5 - and edits in up to 18bit, and has natural-media
tools. Not what I use it for (got Opalpaint, soon to get a Pentium and
Fractal), just correcting a point. I've seen nothing on the PC which comes
close for speed, flexibility and ease of use. Wish there was, but there's not.
Pretty rare you need 24 bit to edit and animate a company logo, or do cel
animation.

Horses for courses, seems to be the lesson. There's just no PC horse for the
course...
