@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Sat, 24 Feb 1996 17:10:58 -0700 " link day.24 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Dave Wilson " link from 0539} @{i}<darius@CONNECT.AB.CA> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Lensflares?" link subj 0958}
---
At 06:36 PM 2/24/96 -0500, you wrote:
@{i}>Why are lensflares desireable? Isn't it just imitating a camera flaw?
@{ui}@{i}>Same question about motion blur.
@{ui}

                I agree with you about lensflares,  I think there are only a
few instances when lensflares are needed.  I've been watching closely lately
for times when lensflares are seen in real world film and video work and
it's a very rare thing.

                Motion blur however is a very required thing when having an
object move across your screen really quickly.  If you go out and rent the
movies Jason and the Argonauts or Clash Of The Titans you'll see varius
scenes of stop motion animation where the frames are perfectly in focus on
every frame.  This makes the animation look as if it is very fake, as if it
was just animation.  However, if you go out and rent Jurrasic park and pause
when the Galli's are flocking by you'll see that there is motion blur
everywhere which helps to add realizm.  Actually the video of the making of
Jurrassic Park has a really good example of the differences and why it's
good to have Motion Blur.  Check it out.
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
