@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Mon, 26 Feb 1996 18:57:45 +0100 " link day.26 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Per Sverre Wold-Hansen " link from 1075} @{i}<woldh@MOTHER.NORCONNECT.NO> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"More flares (Was: Encyclopaedia Lensflaria)" link subj 0366}
---
@{i}> The most know lensflare probably comes from Lightwave renderings
@{ui}@{i}>(everybody should know LW-flares!) but in real world, the physics of the
@{ui}@{i}>lensflare depend upon which lenses you are using with your camera. There's
@{ui}@{i}>...(SNIPP)
@{ui}@{i}> Anders Lundholm .  Alien Workshop (Tm) Computer Graphics
@{ui}
..and also upon the atmosphere...

The LW flare-options DO include options for this kind of halo effects
- I.e. WITHOUT consideration to the LENS.

I used it recently where a logo was slowly drifting across the picture
in front of the "sun". In a combination with a regular "lens-halo" I
got a very nice-looking effect:

When the sun was seen beside the logo, the logo itself (the whole
picture, in fact) got a reduced contrast due to the
dirt-on-the-lens-(halo-)effect.

When the logo then slowly moved in front of the sun, the
lens-effect GRADUALLY tapered off frame by frame (like pictures
you've seen of the sun just disappearing/appearing behind the moon
during an eclipse) - and finally the atmospheric halo of
the sun was seen only BEHIND the backlit (high contrast) logo.

THAT is the kind of effects I would have loved to see
available in the Imagine-of-tomorrow!


     ** Per Sverre **
    Fredrikstad Norway
     woldh@sirius.no


