@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Mon, 26 Feb 1996 13:12:13 -0800 " link day.26 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Chuck Needham " link from 0445} @{i}<twobit@GLOBALDIALOG.COM> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Network support in Winimagine ?" link subj 1033}
---
Andreas Torner wrote:
@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> Hi everyone!
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> Does ne1 know if there is going to be network support in Winimagine ?
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> That is that you can split up a rendering process on the computers
@{ui}@{i}> connected to the network, like in 3D-Studio (if im not wrong).
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}
Have you tried accessing the same project directory on several machines
on the network, say 3 machines. On machine 1 set up a render of the scene
from frame 1 to 997 at a step of 3, machine 2 set up from frame 2 to 998
at a step of 3, and on machine 3, frame 3 to 999 at a step of 3,
logically it should work. Each of the frames are rendered by
numbered-frame name into the pic directory of the co-selected project.

anybody know if it WON'T work?

I know that Imagine won't distribute the rendering of a single frame
(REAL distributed processing) and neither will 3DS.

3DS network render will keep track of frames rendered automatically, so
if one machine goes down, the unrendered frames are redistributed to the
other machines in the setup. The Imagine setup must be manually
maintained.

Oh well.

--
