@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Mon, 26 Feb 1996 12:32:13 -0800 " link day.26 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"John Prusinski " link from 0806} @{i}<jprusins@CYBERGRAFIX.COM> @{ui}
@{i}
@{ui}@{i}>I can start with a sphere, slice it with a cylinder to make the holes,
@{ui}@{i}>then scale it, but then how do i connect the holes up to make it appear
@{ui}@{i}>solid?  I guess I could try to put a cylinder in to connect the holes,
@{ui}@{i}>but I was hoping for an easier solution.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}
@{ui}@{i}When you slice the sphere with a cylinder, what you should end up with is
@{ui}@{i}1)an axis with all resulting parts grouped to it; 2)your original sphere
@{ui}@{i}with the holes cut out of it; 3)the faces of the sphere that were inside the
@{ui}@{i}cylinder; 4)the part of the cylinder that was outside the sphere; and 5)the
@{ui}@{i}part of the cylinder that was inside the sphere.
@{ui}@{i}
@{ui}@{i}If you save 2) and 5), throw away the rest, and then Join 2) and 5), you
@{ui}@{i}should end up with what you're looking for....
@{ui}@{i}
@{ui}@{i}John.
@{ui}@{i}________________________
@{ui}@{i}John Prusinski/CyberGrafix
@{ui}@{i}jprusins@cybergrafix.com
@{ui}@{i}
@{ui}@{i}"Whoever undertakes to set himself up as judge in the field of Truth and
@{ui}@{i}Knowledge is shipwrecked by the laughter of the gods."    A. Einstein
@{ui}

