@node 1046 "Message number 1046"

@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Tue, 27 Feb 1996 00:02:51 +0100 " link day.27 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Per Sverre Wold-Hansen " link from 1075} @{i}<woldh@MOTHER.NORCONNECT.NO> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: how do i extrude in 3 dimensions?" link subj 1472}
@{i}              <3131F612.15E@cswnet.com>
@{ui}---
@{i}>>I want to take a sphere, with a hole in it, and extrude it while expanding
@{ui}@{i}>>the
@{ui}@{i}> sphere.
@{ui}
@{i}>Your question is a little confusing. A sphere is a 3d object and
@{ui}@{i}>"extruding" is usually used to mean taking a 2d object and expanding it
@{ui}@{i}>into the 3rd dimension. To enlarge a sphere you would "scale" it. If you
@{ui}@{i}>want to "drill" a hole through it, you would use a cylinder and "slice"
@{ui}@{i}>it. If none of these is what you want to do, then a little more
@{ui}@{i}>explanation is in order.
@{ui}
@{i}>Rick
@{ui}
I too find the description slightly confusing. It does, however, bring
to mind an extrusion of a spherical object towards its center which
I performed some time ago which might be helpful to some:

I had available the continents of the globe as a one-layer spherical
surface only. (No ocean areas. Just dry land areas with "holes"
where the ocean would be. (Got it from a LightROM.)

I wanted to make a globe with the continents protruding as solid
bodies from the ocean.

So I extruded the surface far back from the initial surface
and got a REALLY weird object.

I then used a JOIN on ALL the points at the "far end" of the extrusion
and got ONE SINGLE POINT which I moved to 0,0,0. So now all
continents went all the way down to the earth center.

When adding a spherical "waterglobe" to 0,0,0 with slightly smaller
diameter I got my continents-protruding-out-of-the-ocean globe.


     ** Per Sverre **
    Fredrikstad Norway
     woldh@sirius.no


			@{"   Return  to  Main    " link main}
			@{"Return to Natural Index" link natural}
@endnode
@node 1047 "Message number 1047"

@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Mon, 26 Feb 1996 17:59:22 -0500 " link day.26 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Craig Andera " link from 0510} @{i}<CANDERA@RFC.COM> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Bowling Ball" link subj 0089}
---
Another way to do it is to punch a hole in your sphere, then extrude
along Y with a very small number (e.g. 0.001), while at the same time
setting your scaling factors large. The object won't go anywhere to
speak of, but it will get bigger.

Not having Imagine in front of me, the only drawback I can think of is that
the extrude requestor might not have a way to scale in Y. In that case,
you're back to replicating, scaling, and joining.

-Craig


			@{"   Return  to  Main    " link main}
			@{"Return to Natural Index" link natural}
@endnode
