@node 1051 "Message number 1051"

@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Mon, 26 Feb 1996 17:50:08 -0700 " link day.26 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Roger Straub " link from 1195} @{i}<straub@CSN.NET> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Lensflares?" link subj 0958}
---
On Sat, 24 Feb 1996, Tom Ross wrote:

@{i}> Why are lensflares desireable? Isn't it just imitating a camera flaw?
@{ui}@{i}> Same question about motion blur.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}
I wrote a long and rambling near-flame about this very subject. These are
both to simulate natural reality, which can get quite difficult to model
sometimes. The ultimate goal of all 3D software is to simulate reality to
the point where we can create something totally unnatural, but the viewer
will accept it as real because it _looks_ so real. Seeing an F1 racer
flash by the camera without any blur would look cheezy. So would a
flareless flashlight pointed directly at the camera.

--
"There is no love sincerer than the love of food."  -- George Bernard Shaw

See ya,
        Ben

