@{i}>I remember first seeing Bridge on the River Kwai, when Alec Guinness is
@{ui}@{i}>looking up at the blistering sun in the jungle. When it glinted so
@{ui}@{i}>blindingly through the trees in his semi-delirium I thought, This is how
@{ui}@{i}>the camera is seeing this. Gosh, it makes me feel tired and hot!
@{ui}
Exactly. Any tools they can give us to help evoke emotion, we'll take with
open arms! (Says a guy who makes TV commercials and training videos :)

@{i}>If reason 2 prevails, we are now becoming accustomed to the look of
@{ui}@{i}>computer graphics, and may begin to call it more real than photography!
@{ui}@{i}>These media are all, of course, filters of a Reality that we couldn't
@{ui}@{i}>comprehend even if we could perceive it.
@{ui}
I know in the case of Jurassic Park, it is pretty hard to imagine how they
could make it any more real, it was so totally convincing. Seems odd that
computers are helping make photography less real, and CG more real.
Maybe it has something to do with photographers having no problem capturing
reality (?) and are now interested in more expressionistic, less constrained
photography. Where will CG go, now that realism has been virtually conquered?
I suspect for the next 3 or 4 years, we'll just start to accept, or in many
cases not even be aware of, the use of CG as it's refined, then the high-end
guys will start to head out into "expressionism" and things will get really
interesting. Well, more interesting, anyway.
