On Mon, 26 Feb 1996 17:59:22 -0500  Craig Andera wrote:
@{i}>Another way to do it is to punch a hole in your sphere, then extrude
@{ui}@{i}>along Y with a very small number (e.g. 0.001), while at the same time
@{ui}@{i}>setting your scaling factors large. The object won't go anywhere to
@{ui}@{i}>speak of, but it will get bigger.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>Not having Imagine in front of me, the only drawback I can think of is that
@{ui}@{i}>the extrude requestor might not have a way to scale in Y. In that case,
@{ui}@{i}>you're back to replicating, scaling, and joining.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>-Craig
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}
There is another way. After pucnhing the hole, select all faces and extrude
along the Y axis far enough so that all the new faces go beyond the original
sphere. Note this distance. Once extruded, go into points mode and select
all the points of the newly extruded faces. Now move them back along the Y
axis by the noted distance above. With the points still selected press S to
scale and drag your mouse to scale the points up or down. What you'll end up
with is one sphere inside another with faces connecting the cutout opening
of the inner and outer sphere. Is this what you want.

- Bob

