@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Tue, 27 Feb 1996 21:02:03 GMT " link day.27 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Robert Darke " link from 1167} @{i}<robda@PARALLEL.DEMON.CO.UK> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Unsliced!" link subj 1369}
---
Hi Harry,

@{i}> Third, and to get to my real subject,  I'm struggling to understand Slice.
@{ui}@{i}> I'm another coverdisk convert, and though I've tracked down a number of
@{ui}@{i}> references to Slice, nowhere have I yet found an explanation of the basic
@{ui}@{i}> operation of doing it. I spent something like an hour on it last night,
@{ui}@{i}> achieved it once, then couldn't repeat the operation. I end up with a fine
@{ui}@{i}> collection of axes and links, and no gretaer understanding than I began
@{ui}@{i}> with. It's obviously a crucial tool, so please, how do I use it?
@{ui}
It's quite an easy concept.

Take two objects, say a plane and a sphere.

Make the plane 100 units across and the sphere diameter 25 units (for
example).

Put the plane three-quarters of the way up the sphere (i.e. sphere axis
centered on 0,0,0, plane axis centered on errm .. 0,0, oh say 15)

Select both objects (shift key)

Select SLICE.

Wait.

You will get four objects ...

1) Bottom of sphere (minus part above plane)

2) Top of sphere (minus part below plane)

3) Plane with hole in middle (where the sphere touched it)

4) The bit out of the middle of the plane.

5) oh, and an axis to be the parent of the group .. forgot that one :-)

Slice basically takes all the objects you have selected and "slices" them
wherever they intersect.

As a consequence, if you have, for example, an object that consists of two
spheres that aren't touching and you slice it, you'll separate the spheres
into individual objects plus an axis as their group-parent.

Hope this helps :-) This is my first IML post ...



Rob

