@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Robin Luiten " link from 1183} @{i}<luiten@TRANTOR.NMSD.OZ.AU> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: Slicing stuff" link subj 1269}
---
@{i}> In a message dated 96-02-28 01:18:29 EST, you write:
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> >One little thing I'd add to Toms advice about slice is that if you get
@{ui}@{i}> >that silly error message (a face is too close to a face, or something like
@{ui}@{i}> >that) you can also try scaling your cutting tool by like .999 and trying
@{ui}@{i}> >again. More times than not this seems to help.
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> Actually David I think the best advice for the slice problem is for everyone
@{ui}@{i}> to flood Impulse with requests that it be fixed.  It is a critical feature
@{ui}@{i}> that does not work properly.  I never realized how important it was until I
@{ui}@{i}> started painlessly slicing solids in Acad and exporting objects into Imagine
@{ui}@{i}> for further work.  It seems such a crucial tool as is the function which
@{ui}@{i}> leaves just the intersection of two objects.  I'm not sure of the difference
@{ui}@{i}> in the programming, perhaps it is just easier to program a solids modeler to
@{ui}@{i}> slice than what we are using in Imagine.  Is there anyone who knows the
@{ui}@{i}> difference who can answer that?
@{ui}
Damn. straight its easier in a solids modeller. Much much easier.

For that matter its easier in Lightwave for only one reason. They
don't have to break all cut polygons into triangles. Therefore there
is less complexity in the object and a lower probability of the
slice [boolean] getting really complex.

If you actually do several booleans in lightwave or get objects
to a complex state that has lots of polygons it too starts barfing....
As an example if you get your Lightwave object and Triple it to make
all polygons triangles then try slicing [boolean] it becomes most
frustrating as well.

One nice thing in Lightwave though is that you can take a 2-D shape
and apply it to the object as a rigid cheese wire to get a cut projected
through the object on the edges of the 2-D shape. This is a simpler
operation than a fully blown slice and if it were implemented might
allow the avoidance of a full slice. With a lower possiblity of failing.

NOTE: I have played with 3D Studio several months ago and it barfs
pretty quick doing 3-D booleans as well. So I don't know how much
bugging impulse is going to help you or your case.

If you can think of some other facility [like maybe the 2-D slice] or
something else that might avoid the complexity of a fully blow 3-D slice
it would be worth airing to see if it can't be turned into a descent
description of something usefull. [Once you have hte description then
it might be worth approaching Impulse with...]

Of course if someone knows how to improve the 3-D slice then by
all means speak up and let Impulse know how it might be improved.

Robin Luiten


