@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Per Sverre Wold-Hansen " link from 1075} @{i}<woldh@MOTHER.NORCONNECT.NO> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: More Edge Line" link subj 1001}
---
@{i}>Take two identical default open ended tubes and place the end of one near,
@{ui}@{i}>but not touching the end of the other.
@{ui}@{i}>Join the two tubes.
@{ui}@{i}>Go to pick edge mode and pick all the edges at the end of one tube.
@{ui}@{i}>Set edge line.
@{ui}@{i}>Clear.
@{ui}@{i}>Pick all the edges at the facing end of the other tube.
@{ui}@{i}>Fill to edge line.
@{ui}@{i}>Result: the edges are connected, but most of the edges on each tube are
@{ui}@{i}>connected to a single edge on the other tube! The result looks rather like
@{ui}@{i}>two distorted and overlapping cones have been placed between the tubes.
@{ui}
I just tried this and do not understand the problems you're
having.

It seams up without a hitch for me on AMIGA, Imagine v4.0.

I even tried selecting points starting at diagonal opposite
points at the second side when before "Fill to Edge Line".
Imagine STILL seamed the two pieces together connecting the
points closest to eachother.

Just a mention: I DID use open-ended tubes made by extruding
a (deafult) disk after removing the central point.

And I picked the edges around the periphery (?)
(perimeter ?? - Whatever) of the two ends by first hiding all
points at the far ends, then turning the remaining points
slightly in perspective view and increased perspective
- Then used "Newmode".


