@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Wed, 28 Feb 1996 15:02:17 -0700 " link day.28 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Roger Straub " link from 1195} @{i}<straub@CSN.NET> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: More Edge Line" link subj 1001}
---
On Wed, 28 Feb 1996, Jon Rubin wrote:

@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> For a simplified example (obviously, I probably wouldn't bother to go
@{ui}@{i}> through all this for such a simple situation, but the problem is evident
@{ui}@{i}> even here):
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}> Take two identical default open ended tubes and place the end of one near,
@{ui}@{i}> but not touching the end of the other.
@{ui}@{i}> Join the two tubes.
@{ui}@{i}> Go to pick edge mode and pick all the edges at the end of one tube.
@{ui}@{i}> Set edge line.
@{ui}@{i}> Clear.
@{ui}@{i}> Pick all the edges at the facing end of the other tube.
@{ui}@{i}> Fill to edge line.
@{ui}@{i}> Result: the edges are connected, but most of the edges on each tube are
@{ui}@{i}> connected to a single edge on the other tube! The result looks rather like
@{ui}@{i}> two distorted and overlapping cones have been placed between the tubes.
@{ui}
I got a good result, with none of the twisting you describe, even when I
flipped one tube around the X axis so that the other end was facing the
first tube, and even when I rotated the bottom tube at an odd angle. The
faces came out looking just fine.


