In a message dated 96-02-28 01:18:51 EST, Stephen G. wrote:

@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>Yeah, and even if it wasn't a SCSI connection on the card if you have a
@{ui}@{i}>dedicated hard drive even with ISA you can still get fast enough throughput
@{ui}@{i}>for full screen video.  The PAR has been doing it for a few years now!
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>So there!  :)
@{ui}@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>s.g.
@{ui}
I'm not sure if I understand this right. You mean to say that your PAR has
been playing back full screen video through your ISA bus to your computer
monitor? I have both the PAR and the Perception and neither of them do that.

Here is how my PAR and Perception have always worked: The frames of my
animation are rendered to the PAR board (through the ISA bus) which
compresses the frames and stores them in a single file on the dedicated
drive. When I want to play back the animation at 30 frames per second, the
dedicated drive sends the file to the PAR board for decompression and
conversion to an NTSC signal and then on to the PAR's S-video, composite and
component outputs which are connected to an NTSC monitor--not my computer
monitor. In doing this, the playback completely bypasses the ISA bus to my
computer. As far as the PAR is concerned, the ISA bus is for nothing more
than power and software communication.

The Perception does have a player that can play back the animation file on
the computer monitor (through the PCI bus) but it is the herky-jerky AVI type
of playback. It is only for those times when reaching over to turn on the
television monitor is just more effort than it is worth.

If it is true your PAR is playing back your animations full screen on your
computer monitor through your ISA bus, then you must have a model of the PAR
that I have never heard of. As a matter of fact, you may have a model that
even Digital Processing Systems (the makers of the PAR and Perception) has
never heard of.

Curtis Carlson
Curtcee@aol.com


