---
Dave Wilson wrote:
@{i}>
@{ui}@{i}>                 I have always thought the Amiga's Arexx was a port of the
@{ui}@{i}> PC's Rexx.  Now I have no idea where I got that from but I'm sure that Arexx
@{ui}@{i}> is a copy of some other OS' Rexx.  Which OS had Rexx first  and why doesn't
@{ui}@{i}> the PC have it?
@{ui}@{i}> Rexx was written in 1979 by Mike Cowlishaw as a language for IBM
@{ui}mainframes and minicomputers (he worked for IBM.)  There are versions
of Rexx for many operating systems now, including Windows and DOS, and
of course the Amiga.  It is also a native command language for OS/2.
Unless it's been updated for Windows 95 or NT, the Windows and DOS versions
don't have the interprocess communication abilities that Amiga users
are used to (I'm not sure about the OS/2 version.)


