@node 1192 "Message number 1192"

@{b}Date:@{ub}         @{"Thu, 29 Feb 1996 17:14:56 -0500 " link day.29 }
@{b}From:@{ub}         @{"Charles Blaquiere " link from 0396} @{i}<blaq@IO.ORG> @{ui}
@{b}Subject:@{ub}      @{"Re: hello" link subj 1468}
---
On Wed, 28 Feb 1996, fernando Bartra wrote:

@{i}>   1- I only have a 4000amiga w 6mb and I'm thinking of getting an extra
@{ui}@{i}> 4mb simms.  Since Im a college student I need to make the most of my
@{ui}@{i}> money.  Will that extra 4mb make a difference in using Imagine?  Does extra
@{ui}@{i}> memory reduces render time?
@{ui}
I don't believe adding RAM will speed Imagine up, since by default it
doesn't use virtual memory on the Amiga. On a PC running Windows,
programs can access more RAM than exists on your computer, by swapping
pages of RAM to/from a hard disk file called the "swap file", naturally.
This allows programs to pretend they have all the RAM they need, but
since hard disks are much, much slower than real RAM, anything that
requires data temporarily stored in the swap file, will get hit with a
large slowdown, as underused parts of RAM are written out to disk, in
order to make room to read the data you need. This is why on a PC, you
can improve speed by buying more RAM, since Windows includes virtual
memory support. On an Amiga, you need a third-party VM utility; if
you're not running this, then your 6M is all Imagine can use.

Adding memory to an Amiga that doesn't run a virtual memory utility,
will allow you to create more complex objects and scenes in Imagine, but
will not accelerate the rendering process.

@{i}>    2- Is it worth upgrading to Imagine 4.0?  As I said, I cannot afford
@{ui}@{i}> much until I graduate in 2 years and I rather get the 4mb.
@{ui}
This is an interesting call. Here's one way to look at it: having only
6M of RAM is a limiting factor, which you'll bump into regularly as you
become ambitious and create complex objects. If you upgrade to 4.0,
you'll have more toys (i.e. software functions) to play with, but that
6M limit will still haunt you. However, if you buy 4 more Megs and don't
upgrade, you'll still have all those 3.0 functions to learn and play
with, but with less frustration. If it were me, I'd choose to be able to
play with less functions, but be better able to enjoy them, rather than
have more functions, but be equally frustrated.

@{i}>    3- I have a few nice cycle anim objects for imagine (knight, dragons,
@{ui}@{i}> etc) and using the cycle editor I can see the different slides that make
@{ui}@{i}> up the cycle and even animate it in wireframe.  Problem is i cant render
@{ui}@{i}> so I go to scenerey animator and try to load cycle but it only loads the
@{ui}@{i}> first obj.  Can I make an anim having all slides of cycle in scenery editor?
@{ui}
Cycles are used in the Action editor. Once you've loaded the object in
your scene, Save Changes and go to the Action editor. Change the "Max. #
frames" at the top from 1 to the desired animation length, for example
30 frames. Then, change the Actor bar for your object, entering the
desired number of cycles you wish to be performed, in the duration of
the bar. (If the bar only stretches from frame 1 to 1, you need to
change its end frame to 30) You can enter fractional numbers of cycles,
too, if you wish.


